WEBVTT

00:05.873 --> 00:10.976
♪ ♪

00:11.145 --> 00:13.245
SUE: I got hit with a
decent amount of snow.

00:13.280 --> 00:16.448
The thing that happens here
is, you get a bunch of snow,

00:16.484 --> 00:18.717
but then the
wind sends it all the way
out to the Arctic Ocean.

00:21.522 --> 00:25.124
Next time, the north wind
comes in and sends it
back down to Fairbanks.

00:25.426 --> 00:27.960
You don't know when a
blizzard's going to come up.

00:27.995 --> 00:31.163
But this right here,
this is why I got to get
the tracks on everything.

00:32.533 --> 00:35.734
On the Argo, the tires
don't make it through
snow like this.

00:35.770 --> 00:37.202
My clearance isn't that much.

00:37.238 --> 00:39.805
You reach a point,
even though it's
got a powerful engine,

00:39.840 --> 00:43.442
the tires will just
start spinning on this,
this wet, heavy snow.

00:46.747 --> 00:50.182
As the temperature
and the conditions change,
your vehicles have to

00:50.217 --> 00:51.650
morph with the times.

00:51.685 --> 00:53.685
Welcome to the next
eight months up in Kavik.

00:54.288 --> 00:56.855
It can be a desolate,
harsh climate.

00:56.891 --> 00:59.992
But it's teeming with
its own forms of life.

01:00.027 --> 01:02.261
If I don't get this done,
I won't be one of them.

01:03.631 --> 01:09.268
(theme music plays).

01:29.490 --> 01:35.027
The tires have to drive on
track and then somehow, I got
to get it to curl back over.

01:35.229 --> 01:37.496
I'm, I just, I'm, I'm
unclear how to do that.

01:37.531 --> 01:39.965
I've been extremely worried.

01:40.000 --> 01:42.301
Spent all night awake,
trying to figure out
how the heck I'm going to

01:42.336 --> 01:45.637
do this because I know
it's, it's a two-person job.

01:46.006 --> 01:48.540
It's not a one-person job.

01:49.076 --> 01:51.844
I enjoy problem solving.

01:51.879 --> 01:55.013
Sometimes, I can get
a little frustrated.

01:59.620 --> 02:03.055
It doesn't stop me from
getting my job done.

02:03.090 --> 02:06.492
Because I'm the only
one here doing the job.

02:14.869 --> 02:17.236
Oh, yeah, right.

02:17.271 --> 02:20.672
Seriously, seriously?

02:20.708 --> 02:22.941
So, how far off am I?

02:22.977 --> 02:26.812
Several inches.

02:26.847 --> 02:31.483
So, I just need to
think how I'm going to get
these two pieces together.

02:31.852 --> 02:35.687
There's slack, if you look,
you've got a little dip here.

02:35.923 --> 02:38.690
A little dip there.
A little dip here.

02:38.726 --> 02:44.930
But if the tires are full,
I might be able just to
take air out of the tires.

02:46.350 --> 02:50.068
Is it key for me to
get my tracks put on and
winterize these vehicles?

02:50.104 --> 02:53.005
Absolutely.

02:53.040 --> 02:56.475
As the planet changes,
I'm getting more snow.

02:56.510 --> 03:01.813
I went and had three foot
of snow and down below
zero temps early on.

03:01.849 --> 03:04.449
Now, it's warmer temps, make
hay while the sun shines.

03:05.186 --> 03:08.086
Get the chores
done when your fingers
aren't going to freeze.

03:08.122 --> 03:13.058
I have more viable time to
work without a glove at 20
above than I do at 20 below.

03:16.197 --> 03:19.731
See if it's making
any difference yet.

03:20.501 --> 03:23.869
It's coming together.

03:24.872 --> 03:28.407
That fits really well now.

03:28.442 --> 03:31.510
Moving, and voila.

03:31.946 --> 03:34.413
Once you get one,
boom, boom, boom, boom.

03:34.448 --> 03:35.881
It's like a zipper.

03:35.916 --> 03:38.550
It, it'll start coming
together better.

03:41.989 --> 03:44.556
Ratchet in a little
tighter on that side.

03:47.995 --> 03:51.096
Okay, there we go.

03:51.115 --> 03:53.532
One side done.

03:54.235 --> 03:57.569
The second one, I'm going to
do just like I did the first.

03:57.605 --> 04:00.706
I might have made
it a little harder than
it needed to be by being

04:00.741 --> 04:02.708
inexperienced at doing it.

04:02.743 --> 04:04.943
But guess what, I got it done.

04:04.979 --> 04:08.513
I guarantee you, by the time
next winter rolls around,
there's a whole new game plan

04:08.549 --> 04:10.482
for how to do this.

04:10.550 --> 04:13.819
It's never about being
stagnant, it's about
using your time wisely.

04:13.854 --> 04:16.989
Work smarter, not harder.

04:19.627 --> 04:23.829
Today, uh, getting
these tracks on, took
up all of my day.

04:23.864 --> 04:27.299
All of my chore allocation
time went on that.

04:28.569 --> 04:32.271
But overall,
a job only takes as
long as it's supposed to.

04:33.007 --> 04:36.074
But for tonight, it's
lights out, and mama's
putting her feet up.

04:41.448 --> 04:42.914
CHIP: This kind of
life is healthy.

04:42.983 --> 04:45.083
You're not overweight,
you're not struggling.

04:45.119 --> 04:47.953
This is just like
a good workout.

04:59.333 --> 05:02.284
Yeah, we got about two
hours of sunlight left.

05:02.569 --> 05:04.036
We can go get this done.

05:04.071 --> 05:05.837
<i> NARRATOR: For the Hailstones,</i>

05:05.873 --> 05:08.540
<i> trapping furbearing</i>
<i> animals this time of</i>
<i> year is a way of life</i>

05:08.575 --> 05:10.342
<i> in northwest Alaska.</i>

05:10.377 --> 05:14.079
<i> The hides can be used to make</i>
<i> clothing that will combat</i>
<i> the brutal winter weather.</i>

05:14.114 --> 05:18.684
<i> Or they can be sold for income</i>
<i> to purchase vital resources.</i>

05:18.719 --> 05:22.287
CHIP: Right now, the
ice isn't very thick and
we've got a ton of snow,

05:22.323 --> 05:23.455
which we usually don't have.

05:23.490 --> 05:25.307
And, um, I'm thinking, just
go put out a few traps.

05:25.359 --> 05:28.093
Maybe I can get ahold of a few
foxes or something right now.

05:29.296 --> 05:31.763
I've got, um, body hold traps.

05:31.799 --> 05:33.932
I got leg holds, and
I have snare wire.

05:34.268 --> 05:36.968
So, we're going to have
plenty to do today.

05:37.004 --> 05:38.570
The trap's I've got
are in bags right now.

05:38.605 --> 05:42.407
I dyed them, and I've
boiled them, and gotten rid
of all the scent and, um,

05:42.426 --> 05:44.242
basically I don't use my
working gloves on them.

05:44.278 --> 05:47.879
I wouldn't want them smelling
like gasoline or like myself,
or something I've touched

05:47.915 --> 05:49.481
around the house.

05:49.516 --> 05:52.150
And, um, they're pretty
much scent free and they're
pretty much ready to go.

05:54.138 --> 05:56.672
I'm going to go to a
lake over here, it's about
2 miles away, 3 miles away.

05:56.707 --> 05:59.308
The best thing I could get it
would probably be a wolverine.

05:59.343 --> 06:01.743
What I'm really kind of
just looking for is some
foxes because foxes tan

06:01.779 --> 06:04.880
quickly and easily, and make a
really great hat.

06:04.915 --> 06:07.950
When you're out at 40 below
and you got a nice fox
hat, then you stay warm.

06:07.985 --> 06:09.718
You can't have too
many furs right now.

06:09.753 --> 06:11.086
It's just one of those things.

06:11.121 --> 06:13.222
It's like a commodity to us.

06:15.626 --> 06:17.159
AGNES: You see those
fox tracks over there?

06:17.194 --> 06:19.061
CHIP: I'm going to go have a
look and see what's doable.

06:20.030 --> 06:21.797
AGNES: Is that a good spot?

06:21.832 --> 06:23.398
Should I untie the sled?

06:23.400 --> 06:25.000
CHIP: Yeah, would you, please?

06:25.035 --> 06:26.668
I've got one good
spot right here.

06:26.704 --> 06:28.937
I'm going to put leg holds.

06:30.941 --> 06:33.575
AGNES: I'm glad we brought
this whole skin so we
can just pick and choose,

06:33.811 --> 06:36.345
and let the hairs
fly as you cut it and
set it for your bait.

06:36.547 --> 06:38.080
CHIP: Oh, yeah, some of
the best bait there is.

06:38.115 --> 06:41.717
AGNES: We've seen a few
tracks and that's why we
decided to trap this area.

06:42.553 --> 06:44.353
CHIP: I'm putting up
some bait right here.

06:44.388 --> 06:46.788
I'm going to put a couple
leg holds underneath it.

06:46.824 --> 06:49.291
Well, I like this spot
because I see a regular
trail going by it,

06:49.326 --> 06:51.760
and I know an animal's
going to pass by here.

06:51.795 --> 06:52.894
Particularly one I want.

06:52.930 --> 06:54.496
And I want a fox right now.

06:54.531 --> 06:56.665
Usually, I set
these in tandem.

06:56.700 --> 06:58.033
Set two of them together.

06:58.068 --> 06:59.835
I've got twice the
luck that way, I guess.

06:59.870 --> 07:02.037
The animal can't really,
uh, go anywhere with them.

07:02.072 --> 07:05.107
He gets two of these on
his legs and he's done for.

07:05.743 --> 07:09.278
And I'm using the caribou
hair to kind of make
a scent or something,

07:09.313 --> 07:12.914
something the animal can pick
up on, thinking that there's
probably something buried here

07:12.950 --> 07:15.017
that it can dig up and eat.

07:15.286 --> 07:17.753
Okay, that's as good
as it gets, I guess.

07:20.658 --> 07:24.226
Think we'll go down here and
get inside the slough, and
take ourselves up the slough.

07:26.497 --> 07:28.497
You want to put a
trap right here?

07:28.766 --> 07:29.898
We might as well go
with the leg holds.

07:29.933 --> 07:32.234
AGNES: Yup.

07:33.804 --> 07:35.170
Are you going to
use the fish trap?

07:35.205 --> 07:37.606
CHIP: Yeah, cause we're by
the water, we should use fish.

07:37.641 --> 07:40.542
AGNES: Yeah.

07:43.514 --> 07:45.947
CHIP: I am putting a leg
hold trap into place.

07:45.983 --> 07:49.051
I'm making like a little
place here where I can
snuggle the trap into.

07:53.590 --> 07:56.191
AGNES: This is the, going to
be a fun ride every other day.

07:56.226 --> 07:58.226
CHIP: It's probably going to
be every day, not every other.

07:58.228 --> 08:00.062
With leg holds, you got
to check them every day.

08:00.097 --> 08:01.697
AGNES: What are those
tracks over there?

08:01.732 --> 08:03.365
CHIP: Those are
ptarmigan and fox.

08:03.400 --> 08:06.601
There's a heavy traffic
of fox coming around
this little point here.

08:06.637 --> 08:10.339
AGNES: Next time, I'm going
to bring a .22, so when
we see those ptarmigan,

08:10.374 --> 08:14.409
we can stop and try
to take a few shots.

08:17.081 --> 08:18.080
Good spot, ah?

08:18.098 --> 08:20.515
CHIP: Yup, we'll
be back tomorrow.

08:20.851 --> 08:23.485
AGNES: Yeah,
I'm glad we got done
before it get too dark,

08:24.154 --> 08:27.956
and we have a good trail blazed.

08:30.227 --> 08:32.561
ANDY: One of the
things I've learned over
the years around here is you

08:32.596 --> 08:35.931
don't fight
Mother Nature when she
decides to do something.

08:35.966 --> 08:38.834
Never pays to force
things out here.

08:46.443 --> 08:49.678
Oh, this sled's
seen better days.

08:53.951 --> 08:56.251
Time to build a new sled.

08:56.286 --> 08:58.820
I pretty much destroyed this
one this year on the ice.

08:59.323 --> 09:03.492
So, I'm going to salvage
pieces and parts off of this
sled and build another one.

09:03.794 --> 09:06.661
I've heard that there
is caribou in the area.

09:06.697 --> 09:09.264
And I'm real anxious
to get out and get some
meat because I didn't get a

09:09.299 --> 09:11.566
moose this year.

09:11.568 --> 09:14.269
This is the first
year in many years I
haven't gotten a moose.

09:14.304 --> 09:17.672
And, uh, it left a lot
of anxiety in me for how
am I going to feed myself

09:17.708 --> 09:20.008
through the winter.

09:20.043 --> 09:23.678
Hearing that the caribou are
around right now is really
picking up my spirits and

09:23.680 --> 09:25.313
making me want to get out.

09:25.382 --> 09:27.649
They are kind of a
ghostly type of animal.

09:27.684 --> 09:29.918
They're either here
or they're not.

09:29.953 --> 09:33.855
So, when they come through
the country, you got to go
get them as quick as you can.

09:33.891 --> 09:35.524
It's all driven by
the clock right now.

09:35.559 --> 09:37.426
And the clock's ticking.

09:37.628 --> 09:41.496
I'm feeling pretty
up against the gun right now
to try and get out there and

09:41.532 --> 09:45.267
hunt some of those guys
before they disappear.

09:46.804 --> 09:51.006
The biggest challenge
you always struggle with in
the wintertime is the darkness.

09:51.041 --> 09:53.658
Our days are only four to
five hours of daylight.

09:53.694 --> 09:56.928
It doesn't give you a
lot of time to really
get out and hunt.

09:56.964 --> 10:00.065
You pile on top of that
that this is the time of
the year the Yukon River

10:00.100 --> 10:02.234
is really unpredictable.

10:02.269 --> 10:04.236
Uh, icing happens
really heavily.

10:04.271 --> 10:06.972
The water levels can
fluctuate really quickly.

10:07.007 --> 10:09.808
Overflow can come in
and, uh, cut you off.

10:09.843 --> 10:12.811
Makes for, uh, a lot
of challenges to overcome,

10:12.846 --> 10:15.730
just to get to where
the caribou are at.

10:18.118 --> 10:21.253
All right.
All that for a piece of metal.

10:23.891 --> 10:28.059
I've got all the
raw materials to build this,
between salvaging the skegs

10:28.162 --> 10:30.228
and brand new plastic,

10:30.264 --> 10:33.498
I want to, I want
to run chain all the
way along each one of

10:33.534 --> 10:37.936
these bolts here so that
any time I have a load,

10:37.971 --> 10:40.539
I've got something I
can hook into with my tie down

10:40.574 --> 10:45.544
strap, that's really
strong and firm, and isn't
going to fray and break.

10:45.579 --> 10:48.547
This sled's going to
be able to haul probably
800, 900 pounds at a time.

10:49.917 --> 10:54.152
So, I want to have my tie down
points really, really strong
so I don't have to worry about

10:54.188 --> 10:56.922
things busting when
I'm hauling a load.

10:57.124 --> 10:59.090
Get these things
sharpened up a little bit.

10:59.126 --> 11:02.327
Try and make these to
where they dig into the
ice a little better.

11:05.499 --> 11:07.682
This country's really
hard on your equipment.

11:07.734 --> 11:10.001
Freighting a lot of heavy
loads over rough conditions.

11:10.037 --> 11:12.904
If you get two or three
years out of a sled,
you're doing pretty good.

11:14.842 --> 11:19.544
That's just the way it is, you
have to plan on building new
equipment from time to time.

11:19.746 --> 11:22.781
You have to plan
on maintaining your
equipment all the time.

11:25.185 --> 11:29.654
I'm going to bend this
plastic back up so that I have
a curve here in the front.

11:33.727 --> 11:35.694
Three quarters.

11:37.097 --> 11:39.231
One twelve and three quarters.

11:39.266 --> 11:42.033
All right.
Let's see if I can hit
this thing with some heat.

11:43.203 --> 11:48.273
So, the idea here is just
to heat all this plastic
so that it takes this bend.

11:48.909 --> 11:52.878
Basically, what I'm
doing is I'm relaxing
the plastic right now.

11:54.381 --> 12:00.552
I'm heating it up, spreading
the molecules, and then when
it cools they should stay

12:00.654 --> 12:04.656
right where they're, pretty
close to where they were at.

12:09.696 --> 12:13.198
All right, that
should be hot enough.

12:14.034 --> 12:15.800
Looking good.

12:15.836 --> 12:18.737
I got the sled built,
it's a long night.

12:18.772 --> 12:22.974
And, uh, I think I got
a really good rig here
for multiple purposes.

12:23.343 --> 12:28.713
I'm hoping my first use is
to put some bloody caribou
in it and haul it home.

12:31.752 --> 12:33.685
JESSIE: It's very
easy to be here in the now,

12:33.720 --> 12:36.187
but it's all about
thinking the next
step, the next stage.

12:50.003 --> 12:53.872
Well, we had a good
little cold snap, and, uh,
followed by a bunch of snow,

12:53.907 --> 12:56.775
so we got some ice built
up down here on the
slough and the river.

12:57.644 --> 13:01.813
I'm going to go down there and
look about putting in myself
in a permanent water hole,

13:01.848 --> 13:04.649
that I'll be able to get
water out of all winter.

13:04.685 --> 13:07.018
I don't really have a way
of getting water right here,

13:07.054 --> 13:08.353
so I have to
go down to the river,

13:08.355 --> 13:10.789
which takes a lot of time.

13:11.725 --> 13:13.625
Water is the most
important thing.

13:13.660 --> 13:16.795
Having so many dogs, I use
at least 40 gallons a day.

13:16.830 --> 13:18.663
That dog food cooker
is full of water.

13:18.699 --> 13:20.515
There's broth
for my race dogs.

13:20.567 --> 13:22.467
There's washing
water for everything.

13:22.502 --> 13:26.538
A lot of people think it's
romanticized to live without
electricity or without running

13:26.573 --> 13:29.140
water, but that's not
an option out here.

13:29.176 --> 13:33.578
The only reason I'm able to
afford to do this with my dogs
is because I don't have those.

13:34.481 --> 13:37.449
I got my chainsaw and
my ice pick, that's all
I should need right now.

13:37.484 --> 13:40.051
I'm going to go down
here to the slough and I'm
going to look at what it's

13:40.087 --> 13:42.620
going to take to
get out on that ice.

13:46.093 --> 13:47.759
This year, I got
a snow machine.

13:47.761 --> 13:51.329
The main reason I got the
snow machine is so I can
use it for utilitarian work

13:52.065 --> 13:54.032
that I usually do with the dogs.

13:54.067 --> 13:55.900
Cause usually I'm hauling
all my wood with my dogs.

13:55.936 --> 13:59.938
All the water with my dogs,
the snow machine gives me a
way of doing things faster and

13:59.973 --> 14:02.207
more efficient, while leaving
the dogs out of that picture.

14:02.609 --> 14:05.210
While I like doing
those things with dogs, I'm
trying to be faster and more

14:05.245 --> 14:09.080
efficient, and my, training
my dogs is going to be way
more focused on racing now.

14:11.084 --> 14:14.219
Hopefully, haul a lot
of water in a couple hours
to where I have enough water

14:14.254 --> 14:15.787
for the whole week.

14:15.822 --> 14:18.189
That way, I can
stay ahead of it.

14:22.329 --> 14:25.530
Well, it looks like what
we got going on here
is a lot of overflow.

14:25.565 --> 14:28.933
This was all froze
up pretty good, but all
this snow came and pushed a

14:28.969 --> 14:30.201
bunch of water up.

14:30.237 --> 14:32.070
If you're out in
the wilderness and
you're running dogs,

14:32.105 --> 14:34.506
and you go through overflow,
it can be really dangerous.

14:34.941 --> 14:36.341
Whoa.

14:40.497 --> 14:41.863
JESSIE: Whoa.

14:41.898 --> 14:44.332
Definitely won't be
able to get the snow
machine over this.

14:45.602 --> 14:47.802
Damn that's deep.

14:49.206 --> 14:52.841
So, I need to get out
here and check this ice,
and see how that is.

14:52.876 --> 14:54.843
Uh, hopefully, it's
not as deep here.

14:54.878 --> 14:59.647
See if I can't use
this plywood to disperse my
weight when I walk out there.

14:59.683 --> 15:02.817
And see if I can see how deep
it is out towards the middle.

15:18.135 --> 15:21.970
I had to be careful, you never
know what to expect with ice.

15:29.446 --> 15:32.213
Oh, man (bleep).

15:32.449 --> 15:35.049
Not good.
Not (bleep) good.

15:35.085 --> 15:37.919
Nope, too deep.

15:39.055 --> 15:40.755
This is a pain in
my ass right now.

15:40.791 --> 15:43.258
I can't get the direct
way to the river I wanted.

15:43.293 --> 15:45.460
This has been something I've
been envisioning a long time.

15:45.495 --> 15:49.164
Being able to shoot
right out of my dog yard,
right onto the slough here

15:49.199 --> 15:52.367
with the dogs or
with the snow machine
to haul water and wood.

15:52.369 --> 15:55.537
This isn't going to work out.

15:56.006 --> 15:58.206
I'm not going to be able
to get out on this safely.

15:58.241 --> 16:01.476
I can't risk going out
there and getting wet or
sinking my snow machine.

16:02.545 --> 16:05.680
I'm going to go the longer
way around to the river and
go ahead and start working on

16:05.715 --> 16:08.049
putting my hole in down there.

16:08.084 --> 16:10.185
Cause I need water,
I got to get this hole in,

16:10.220 --> 16:12.821
and I can't wait
for this to freeze up.

16:16.560 --> 16:18.193
CHIP: We spend a lot of time
together, me and the family.

16:18.228 --> 16:21.462
To us, it's just, uh,
another part of living here.

16:31.608 --> 16:33.708
<i> NARRATOR: The Hailstones</i>
<i> are checking the</i>
