Wanted to park a little back,
see if I could see any tracks.

35:28.294 --> 35:31.295
I don't see any
obvious tracks here.

35:33.699 --> 35:38.635
And just like I had hoped,
it's protected from the
snow and whatnot in here.

35:38.871 --> 35:41.104
Twenty-three hits.

35:41.140 --> 35:44.174
So again, that's a
pretty good amount.

35:49.982 --> 35:53.784
I got my game cams,
so let's see what they
saw that I didn't.

35:54.586 --> 35:56.687
What's that?

35:56.922 --> 35:57.954
Oh, look at that!

35:57.990 --> 36:00.057
That little foxy.

36:00.092 --> 36:02.326
Well, little foxy certainly
is curious about it.

36:04.897 --> 36:06.930
Oh, he is messing with it.

36:06.965 --> 36:09.533
Look at, he's bouncing it.

36:09.735 --> 36:11.501
You leave that camera alone.

36:11.537 --> 36:12.669
What are you getting?

36:12.705 --> 36:13.970
Oh, he's getting snow.

36:14.006 --> 36:15.772
He's getting snow for water.

36:15.808 --> 36:19.242
I was unaware that they
would stockpile snow.

36:19.278 --> 36:22.245
It's not like it's a real
limited commodity out here.

36:22.548 --> 36:23.747
Interesting.

36:23.782 --> 36:25.282
Okay, I see an image here.

36:25.317 --> 36:26.550
Look at that.

36:26.585 --> 36:28.218
I almost didn't see
it, it's a ptarmigan.

36:28.253 --> 36:29.552
How well hidden is that?

36:29.555 --> 36:31.321
And he's just sitting there.

36:31.357 --> 36:32.956
Hi, ptarmy.

36:32.991 --> 36:34.958
Look at them all.

36:35.160 --> 36:37.744
Well, this definitely
looks like maybe where I
wanna set up a blind and be

36:37.796 --> 36:39.863
waiting for the ptarmys.

36:39.965 --> 36:42.199
Oh, look at him.

36:42.234 --> 36:43.767
What is he doing?

36:43.802 --> 36:46.169
Scuttling around.

36:46.205 --> 36:49.740
He says, "Yup, I'm going over
here." I'm very pleased with
what I'm catching so far.

36:51.076 --> 36:53.643
It did exactly what
I asked it to do.

36:53.679 --> 36:55.912
They were sensitive enough
to catch a lot of the birds.

36:55.981 --> 36:57.481
They got the foxes.

36:57.516 --> 37:00.484
It's a welcome addition
to the perimeter check.

37:03.856 --> 37:06.156
JESSIE: Opportunity
is something you got
to seize up here.

37:06.191 --> 37:08.959
You wait one second,
it's one second too late.

37:14.400 --> 37:18.602
Dog food, will get one
last stir and that'll
be done when I get back.

37:19.705 --> 37:23.874
It's about the last of the
water I got so the timing
is now to get some more and.

37:25.411 --> 37:28.545
It takes about 40 gallons
a day for me to run the
homestead around here,

37:28.580 --> 37:31.548
and most of that water
goes into keeping my dogs
hydrated and feeding them

37:31.583 --> 37:33.316
good, moist, warm food.

37:33.352 --> 37:36.820
Very good hydration
is critical to
a healthy sled dog.

37:38.557 --> 37:41.024
Time to head down
there and see how the
ramp's doing and, uh,

37:41.059 --> 37:43.727
check the ice and start
getting some water.

38:01.613 --> 38:04.614
All right.
This is the ramp
I put in last night.

38:04.650 --> 38:06.249
There was a drop off here.

38:06.285 --> 38:09.119
There was no way I could
have possibly got the water
buckets up there safely on

38:09.154 --> 38:12.656
the sled but, uh, this
thing is froze up and
set up nice overnight.

38:14.059 --> 38:16.460
Super hard, super gradual.

38:16.495 --> 38:20.363
Gonna head over here and
fill up my water buckets
and give it its first try.

38:32.578 --> 38:34.444
That's hard.

38:34.480 --> 38:36.813
That's soft.

38:39.451 --> 38:41.685
Damn, that's pretty deep.

38:41.720 --> 38:44.287
No way that snow
machine's going over here.

38:44.323 --> 38:48.725
So, I'm gonna put the water
hole here pretty close
so I can carry the buckets.

38:51.797 --> 38:55.165
Right now, I'm just trying to
cut it out without punching
through so I don't spray a

38:55.200 --> 38:57.434
bunch of water over myself.

38:57.469 --> 39:00.086
So I'll get the
outline of the cut.

39:05.210 --> 39:07.944
All right.
So that was pretty easy
to get through right there.

39:08.247 --> 39:11.581
Gotta pop this big
piece of ice out.

39:19.358 --> 39:22.559
Take my gloves off for this
so I don't get my gloves wet.

39:22.594 --> 39:26.196
Enough ice to hold my weight,
but not enough to hold
the snow machine's weight.

39:26.231 --> 39:30.300
Now I just gotta go get my
buckets and fill them up and
take them back to the sled and

39:30.335 --> 39:33.220
then take them home.

39:36.708 --> 39:39.442
You're either working for
water one way or another.

39:39.545 --> 39:42.412
You're either going to work
to pay the water bill or
you're working to come get

39:42.514 --> 39:45.015
it out of the river yourself.

39:45.951 --> 39:48.652
This is the kind
of work I enjoy.

39:48.887 --> 39:51.688
It's not what I had
planned necessarily, but
you got to work with what

39:51.723 --> 39:53.857
the conditions are.

39:53.892 --> 39:56.893
And the ice is still
pretty thin, so I'll
be thankful to have this

39:56.929 --> 39:58.929
waterhole right here.

39:58.964 --> 40:01.831
I don't really wanna
go any further out.

40:05.237 --> 40:07.003
All right, so I got
my sled loaded up.

40:07.039 --> 40:09.739
Now, I just gotta get
it home and get it unloaded
and get back down here and

40:09.775 --> 40:14.544
get some more and, uh,
put a little lid over my
hole so it won't freeze.

40:15.247 --> 40:19.416
Just take it nice
and easy, that way, I
don't spill nothing.

40:25.290 --> 40:27.524
CHIP: There's everything
you possibly need
that we can make a living

40:27.559 --> 40:29.593
from around here.

40:38.770 --> 40:41.805
AGNES: Today, Chip and
I is out here checking
our traps and, uh,

40:41.840 --> 40:44.307
it's just a lot
colder of a day.

40:44.359 --> 40:48.311
We have a stiff wind
going and, uh, it's kinda
chilly out here actually.

40:52.384 --> 40:53.917
AGNES: Oh, look!

40:53.952 --> 40:56.553
CHIP: Yup. Behind the
bush that's a fox.

40:57.489 --> 40:58.622
Right.

40:58.657 --> 41:01.224
You need to aim about
a foot above him.

41:01.493 --> 41:03.059
He's getting ready to run.

41:09.434 --> 41:11.668
CHIP: Oh, man that was close.

41:13.605 --> 41:15.572
You can't do a 200-yard
shot with a .22.

41:15.607 --> 41:16.973
AGNES: Yeah.
CHIP: That's not
going to work.

41:17.009 --> 41:18.808
AGNES: Yup.
CHIP: Way too far for a .22.

41:18.844 --> 41:20.910
AGNES: Hopefully, it'll just
go get stuck in our trap.

41:20.946 --> 41:22.912
That way, I don't have
to put a hole in it.

41:22.948 --> 41:25.615
CHIP: She got pretty close,
but we've got traps to check.

41:25.651 --> 41:27.951
Let's get to going, huh?

41:33.291 --> 41:35.191
Nothing in that one and
nothing in this one.

41:35.227 --> 41:36.493
AGNES: Hmm?

41:36.528 --> 41:38.161
CHIP: But the ravens
are following us.

41:38.196 --> 41:39.396
I saw two of them just
a little while ago.

41:39.431 --> 41:40.830
And this is just
the beginning of it all,

41:40.866 --> 41:42.565
so I need to go get more
traps and I need to go make

41:42.601 --> 41:44.668
more sets and more
sets and more sets.

41:44.703 --> 41:46.002
Well, you wanna go home?

41:46.038 --> 41:48.405
AGNES: Yup.
CHIP: All right.

41:49.474 --> 41:51.041
I'm pretty happy with
the sets I've got.

41:51.076 --> 41:53.043
Pretty soon the
animals will find out
where these things are.

41:53.078 --> 41:55.011
And, uh, they'll
start to produce.

41:55.047 --> 41:58.915
It may not happen today, it
may not happen tomorrow but
I'm just gonna keep checking.

41:58.950 --> 42:00.550
And this is just
the beginning of it all so,

42:00.585 --> 42:02.686
we've got a lot
to look forward to on
this trapping season.

42:02.721 --> 42:07.290
We just gotta give it time
and um, time's gonna happen.

42:09.895 --> 42:13.630
JESSIE: I have to get out of
my comfort zone and get more
into the technological era.

42:13.665 --> 42:15.532
I mean I'm kind of a
primitive dude, you know?

42:15.567 --> 42:18.101
I like the simple
things in life.

42:24.142 --> 42:26.643
Just putting the finishing
touches on my door here.

42:29.915 --> 42:32.048
It's just basically
an insulated box.

42:32.084 --> 42:35.552
If I can keep the
air temperature from
getting into the ice,

42:35.587 --> 42:38.555
then it's gonna keep
it from freezing
so much underneath,

42:38.857 --> 42:41.257
so I don't have to do
as much maintenance.

42:41.526 --> 42:43.693
Less time chipping ice,
more time running dogs.

42:43.729 --> 42:45.962
That's what I'm
trying to accomplish.

42:48.500 --> 42:51.451
Thing I like about this,
it's very nice and simple.

42:52.003 --> 42:56.506
Just like that, my water hole
is protected from the cold.

42:57.943 --> 43:00.910
Now I can go home and,
uh, feed the dogs and
have plenty of water.

43:02.981 --> 43:05.782
Good day to get this done
because I was out of water.

43:06.151 --> 43:09.252
I used the last of the water
this morning for the dog food
cooker and now I'm gonna have

43:09.287 --> 43:12.122
plenty of water, 250
gallons' worth of water.

43:12.524 --> 43:15.058
That's a lot of water,
last me all week.

43:24.536 --> 43:28.204
So I can tell you,
I've had to work way harder
to get water in the past and

43:28.240 --> 43:32.742
I'm pretty happy with,
uh, the new system, with the
snow machine, really helps.

43:33.879 --> 43:36.346
I don't have to bother
hooking up the dogs for that.

43:36.381 --> 43:39.949
We can focus our efforts
more on our training.

43:40.352 --> 43:44.353
For me, the snow machine
is just a tremendous resource
and it's gonna really help me

43:44.422 --> 43:48.658
maximize on the most important
things in my life like
getting wood, getting water,

43:49.461 --> 43:53.463
packing down trails,
breaking trails, going setting
up camps ahead of the dogs

43:53.498 --> 43:55.698
instead of using the dogs
for these things.

43:55.734 --> 43:58.835
That way, I can get
more time and focus on
just running the dogs.

43:59.304 --> 44:01.704
The snow machine's
really gonna unlock a
lot of things for me.

44:01.740 --> 44:04.340
'Cause I mean it's endless
what I can do with that.

44:04.543 --> 44:10.713
I'm all about bettering
my process so I can get more
efficient and I can do more.

44:15.921 --> 44:20.473
ANDY: You learn the
timing when you live
out in the woods.

44:24.846 --> 44:27.947
Oh, there's my lucky caribou.
